that artillery sends units flying everywhere, even high up into the
sky. Characters knock back a swarm of enemies with one swipe, launching
them all backwards. <br>

<br>
So you might be asking at this point.....how the hell am I supposed to
enjoy all this camera angling and unit squishing and such while playing
the game? Currently all that is available is the ability to pause the
game (while still issuing commands) so that you can capture a snap shot
of the action. Fans (including myself) have clamored for a slow motion
toggle so you can watch the battle moving, but Relic has not introduced
this as of yet, probably for balance reasons. <br>
<br>
<span style="font-weight:bold">THEME 
</span><br>

<br>
As a table top Warhammer player, Dawn of War hits a very, very sweet
spot for me. The Warhammer universe is vast, with tons of extra detail,
background, and flavor along with it (known to warhammer players as
"fluff"). Anyone who likes(or loves!) Warhammer has to check this game
out, as it is one of the best presentations of the Warhammer property
in a video game. <br>

<br>
But you don't have to be a warhammer fan to get into Dawn of War. In
translation to an RTS, the units are all documented in a way that any
RTS player will recognize. And if you can't get into the twisted,
bloodsoaked, battle hardened warhammer universe, you don't have a pulse
<br>

<br>
The game enviroments run from runied cities full of blasted statuary
and crumbling buildings, to grassy jungle like settings, and more, all
skinned and textured to capture the feel of Warhammer.. Being in beta,
we were only exposed to about 1/3 of the maps, and no single player
maps, so what I actually know of level designs and appearances is
pretty limited. <br>

<br>
ANALYSIS 
<br>

<br>

<br>
Sound: The sound hits the right notes for the game Relic has produced,
capturing the dark moodiness of the Warhammer world, the deafening roar
of combat, and the agonized screams of the dying. No complaints here. <br>

<br>
Gameplay: Some in beta(there are always a few) claim that DoW is just
another RTS, and that nothing is different, and that strategies are
narrow. I have to say, I disagree almost completely. Strategy seems
limited at first, but as you grow into the game and get comfortable
with the aggressive play, new strategies present themselves every day. <br>

<br>
Personally, I suck at competitive RTS gaming. And yet, I've gotten
fairly good at DoW(66% win ratio) and I play the game as it was
intended, with lots of squads and some small back up from vehicles,
with diversity. So I know that not all the complaints are valid. If I
can win at an RTS game, anyone can do it with the right moves. I'm very
satisfied with Dawn of War's game play. The battles are fun, and very
active, enough to keep the micro manager happy, while visual enough to
keep the relaxed highly entertained. <br>

<br>
Graphics: One of Dawn of War's strongest points. The models are well
done, and contain a lot of detail. Being able to swivel the camera
around is just so cool, especially with all the massed combat. The gun
fire, lasers, artillery, explosions, and all the close combat
animations, give Dawn of War battles a very visceral feel, more so that
most of the other RTS's I've played. There is a real danger in Dawn of
War of watching too much of the game instead of playing it(against
people anyways). <br>

<br>
One of the coolest features is the army painter, where you can color
your units, and attach custom badges and battle standards to them.
Table top warhammer is as much a model painting hobby as it is a game,
and so this is a feature that gets alot of us table top players
excited, being able to field our own special armies in a video game. <br>

<br>Theme: Not much to say here that I haven't said already. The theme
of
Warhammer and much of it's fluff and story was the guiding light for
Dawn of War. Many if not most of their design decisions that took their
lead from the table top game. The&nbsp; actual&nbsp; game mechanics do
not&nbsp; reflect the table top game, they are based off an RTS model,
so if you are a hardcore fan of the <span style="font-weight:bold">table top game system</span>,
Dawn of War will disapoint you in that aspect. However if you love the
theme, look, and feel of 40k, then the Emperor demands you go out and
buy Dawn of War right now. <br>
<br>
Relic really did Warhammer justice with this latest production. 
<br>

<br><span style="font-weight:bold">
PREFORMANCE: 
</span><br>

<br>
Here's where my problems start to arise with Dawn of War. The game
demands alot of your system to put out all those units doing their own
things and all the lights and colors. Currently in the beta, overall
preformance, even on top rigs, is an issue. By scaling down the
textures and resolution, lower end computers can still play Dawn of War
pretty well, but very very few people play the game and have it run
"perfect". <br>

<br>
A lot of this is due in part to the insane amount of texturing Dawn of
War has. In addition to all the individual unit, building, and
enviroment textures, when players start making custom paint jobs and
badges to use in game, the load times become monstrous. In order to
achieve better preformance for everyone playing the multiplayer, custom
badges and banners had the resolution forced down, and all players are
forced down a level of detail. <br>
<br>
While this has not solved all the preformance issues, it has helped. On
a AMD 2600+ Barton, GeforceFX5900XT, and 512 DDR ram, multiplayer runs
fairly well for me, with some slight hitching and hang ups in mass
battles, mainly due to other people's lag. In the single player
tutorial beta testers get, my preformance is not so hot, surprisingly.
With full details on, and all texture levels accounted for, by the time
there are many many units on the screen, the frames noticably suffer.
This is one of those things I hope gets ironed out in release, as
there's no better way to kill your game that having crappy preformance
out of the box. <br>

<br>

<br>

<br>
Final thoughts: 
<br>

<br>
Not very often do I get to review a game this much, while still in
beta(short as it may be now). While I've only played one map against the
comp on single player, and played a bunch of the MP, there is stiill a
whole single player game, based around the Space Marines. Relic did
only one race because they wanted to deliver a strong story to go along
with the single player. If the rest of game is an indicator, the single
player story will prove to be a dark, war torn slaughter fest, just
like the rest of 40k. <br>

<br>
In case you haven't noticed, I'm pretty taken with the game. That says
alot for me when WC3 kept me entertained for all of 3 days, modding and
all. I believe that Dawn of War is a solid, fun game, and it's only
hitch right now is the lack of solid preformance. If Relic can get that
tied up, they will deliver a game that I think will turn the heads of
people walking through the computer games section. <br>

<br>
RATINGS 
<br>
out of a possible 10 
<br>

<br>

<br>
Sound: 7.5 
<br>

<br>
Gameplay: 8.5 
<br>

<br>
Graphics: 8.0 
<br>

<br>
Theme: 10! 
<br>

<br>
Preformance: 6 
<br>
(Sorry Relic. It gets a 6 only because it runs pretty good on my system.....most of the time) 
<br>

<br>

<br>
SCORE: 8/10 
<br>

<br>

<br>
Phew! Thanks for reading! I'm going to bed.<br>
<br>
-Justin "Nenjin" Wheeler<br>
Safehouse Staff Writer<br>
